t </td><td class=\"left\"> </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2006 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Muhammad Yunus </td><td class=\"left\">Bangladesh </td><td class=\"left\">Yes </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">M </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2007 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Al Gore </td><td class=\"left\">USA </td><td class=\"left\">Yes </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">M </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2007 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Intergovern- mental Panel On Climate Change (IPCC) </td><td class=\"left\">USA </td><td class=\"left\">Yes </td><td class=\"left\">Inst </td><td class=\"left\"> </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2008 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Martti Ahtisaari </td><td class=\"left\">Finland </td><td class=\"left\">No </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">M </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2009 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Barack Obama </td><td class=\"left\">USA </td><td class=\"left\">No </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">M </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2010 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Liu Xiaobo </td><td class=\"left\">China </td><td class=\"left\">No </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">M </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2011 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf </td><td class=\"left\">Liberia </td><td class=\"left\">Yes </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">F </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2011 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Leymah Gbowee </td><td class=\"left\">Liberia </td><td class=\"left\">Yes </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">F </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2011 </td><td class=\"bold left\">Tawakkul Kar </td><td class=\"left\">Yemen </td><td class=\"left\">Yes </td><td class=\"left\">Ind. </td><td class=\"left\">F </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">2012 </td><td class=\"bold left\">European Union </td><td class=\"left\">Cross-national </td><td class=\"left\">No </td><td class=\"left\">Inst </td><td class=\"\"> </td></tr>\n      </tbody>\n      <tfoot>\n            <tr>\n              <td colspan=\"6\">\n                <p>SOURCE: <a href=\"http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/2010/\">nobelprize.org</a></p>\n              </td>\n            </tr>\n          </tfoot>\n      </table><p><strong></strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a></p><p>• <a href=\"https://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=0AonYZs4MzlZbdDQyOG5nNmVma1d1LWZDa0FCaTRZZ1E&amp;hl=en\">DATA: download the full spreadsheet</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p><strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/datastore\">Follow us on Twitter</a></strong></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/maps_and_graphs/2011/10/7/1317980013132/Nobel-peace-prize-003.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2011/oct/07/nobel-peace-prize-winners-list-2011","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/news/datablog/2011/oct/07/nobel-peace-prize-winners-list-2011","sectionName":"World news"},{"webTitle":"Rise of the megacities – get the data | Nick Mead","webPublicationDate":"2012-10-04T12:24:00Z","sectionId":"global-development","id":"global-development/datablog/2012/oct/04/rise-megacities-get-data","fields":{"body":"<p>Our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/interactive/2012/oct/04/rise-of-megacities-interactive\">rise of the megacities interactive</a> draws on the UN's latest population estimates and predictions, <a href=\"http://esa.un.org/unup/\">World Urbanisation Prospects</a>. While it is the most commonly cited dataset for city and urban population figures, it is an area fraught with difficulty.</p><p>For starters, what's the best way to define a city? Do you stick with often historical legal and administrative boundaries (the city proper)? Do you, perhaps, use population density so that suburban areas are included and city sprawl captured (urban agglomeration)? </p><p>A more comprehensive concept is that of the metropolitan area, which includes urban agglomerations and surrounding areas of lower density \"under the direct influence of the city\". Under that definition, rural populations can be counted as urban, so long as they fall under the direct political or economic influence of a city.</p><p>The municipal district of Chongqing in south-west China, for example, has a total population of more than 30 million – but less than 6 million live in Chongqing city proper. Depending on which classification is used, Chongqing could be listed as the world's largest city, or not even make the top tier.</p><p>The population division of the UN's Department of Economic and Social Affairs issues estimates every two years (the latest came out in April, the next are due in 2014). To collect the data, the department sends annual questionnaires to more than 230 national statistical offices. But while the <a href=\"http://esa.un.org/unup/Documentation/WUP_glossary.htm\">UN has defined general guidelines</a>, many countries use their own standards.</p><p>Collecting accurate data on city populations is notoriously difficult. Censuses are only conducted once a decade or less – until last year, <a href=\"http://articles.cnn.com/2011-05-03/world/togo.census_1_togolese-first-census-parliamentary-elections?_s=PM:WORLD\">the latest census data available for Lomé in Togo was almost 30 years out of date</a> – while urban populations are often highly mobile and unofficial.</p><p>And the results of surveys and censuses can be manipulated for political ends. For example, China reclassified some rural areas as urban in the 1980s to give it greater administrative control.</p><p>The UN is at least <a href=\"http://esa.un.org/unup/CD-ROM/Documentation/WUP2011-DataSource-UrbanAgglomeration-and-CapitalCities1.xls\">transparent about where it gets the city data from</a>, and its population forecasting model is relatively straightforward. </p><p>David Bloom at Harvard, who conducted a recent <a href=\"http://www.wider.unu.edu/publications/working-papers/2010/en_GB/wp2010-12/\">review of urbanisation data</a>, says the main advantage of the UN model is its \"simplicity and transparency\". But he cautions that it can lead to \"quite unrealistic\" projections: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It requires no detailed data and can thus be readily applied across countries. But the main problem with the model is that it does not have any theoretical foundations: all forecasts are pure extrapolations of past trends and, thus, do not distinguish urbanisation generated by migration from fertility or mortality-driven changes in the composition of the underlying population. The model implicitly assumes that all countries will follow the historical path of now-developed countries and does not take into consideration differences across countries.</p></blockquote><p>A much-cited <a href=\"http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;ved=0CCUQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.iussp.org%2FActivities%2Fwgc-urb%2Fcohen.pdf&amp;ei=ST9kUKXlHI3C0AWIxoHwBQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNGbEAwXoznu-27IUYzNzXgrX4rD5w\">study by Barney Cohen</a>, of the US National Research Council, looked at  UN predictions for 169 countries. Cohen found urban population forecasts made 20 years earlier were on average 14% too high, forecasts made 10 years ago were 17% too high, while forecasts made five years ago were, on average, correct. Projections were most reliable for OECD countries and least reliable for sub-Saharan Africa and other low-income countries.</p><p>The recent, rapid development of global mapping technologies is allowing academics to create more detailed and consistent datasets – although it is a work in progress and the data does not yet have global coverage.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.afd.fr/lang/en/home/publications/travaux-de-recherche/archives-anciennes-collections/NotesetEtudes/Africapolis\">Africapolis</a>, part of the <a href=\"http://www.e-geopolis.eu/\">e-Geopolis</a> project to map and estimate urban populations around the world, cross-references satellite imagery with data from censuses and other official publications to produce estimates for settlements with more than 10,000 residents.</p><p>Africapolis's estimates and predictions for the population of Lagos differ markedly from those produced by the UN.</p><p>Deborah Potts, at King's College, London, says the UN data used is frequently wrong: \"Of the three largest cities in sub-Saharan Africa, for decades we have only been reasonably sure of the size of Johannesburg; Kinshasa's size can only be guessed, and that of Lagos is deeply contested.\"</p><p>At a national level, Africapolis estimated the urbanisation level of Nigeria at 30% in 2006 – compared with the UN's estimate of 49%.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;ved=0CCMQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.kcl.ac.uk%2Fsspp%2Fdepartments%2Fgeography%2Fresearch%2Fepd%2FNigeriaUrbPottsOccPaper39.pdf&amp;ei=jEZkUJCbG6LG0QWpuIDABg&amp;usg=AFQjCNHGTxvkIFAkvP-Qoc9nDNhlA66wWg\">Potts says urbanisation in Nigeria has been significantly overestimated</a>, with major policy implications: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>There can be no doubt that the level has been overestimated as the discrepancy is absolutely enormous: the UN, basing its figures on Nigerian official data, estimated that 69 million Nigerians were living in towns, compared to the Africapolis estimate of 42 million: a difference of 27 million people.</p><p>Far from being rapid, the shift from rural to urban in this part of the world has usually become very gradual or stagnant or, in some cases, reversed. </p></blockquote><p>The rise of megacities interactive uses UN estimates on urban agglomerations with populations above 750,000 from the latest revision to World Urbanisation Prospects. </p><h2>Data summary</h2><table>\n      <caption>\n            UN cities estimates and predictions\n          </caption>\n      <thead>\n        <tr><th class=\"left\">Urban Agglomeration</th><th class=\"left\">Country</th><th class=\"left\">1950 (000s)</th><th class=\"left\">2010 (000s)</th><th class=\"left\">2025 (000s)</th></tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr><td class=\"left\">Kabul </td><td class=\"left\">Afghanistan </td><td class=\"left\">128.93 </td><td class=\"left\">3052 </td><td class=\"left\">5125.92 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">El Djazaïr  (Algiers) </td><td class=\"left\">Algeria </td><td class=\"left\">516.45 </td><td class=\"left\">2850.91 </td><td class=\"left\">3976.73 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Wahran (Oran) </td><td class=\"left\">Algeria </td><td class=\"left\">268.94 </td><td class=\"left\">775.67 </td><td class=\"left\">1025.7 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Huambo </td><td class=\"left\">Angola </td><td class=\"left\">15.31 </td><td class=\"left\">1038.58 </td><td class=\"left\">1996.75 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Luanda </td><td class=\"left\">Angola </td><td class=\"left\">138.41 </td><td class=\"left\">4790.14 </td><td class=\"left\">8924.04 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Buenos Aires </td><td class=\"left\">Argentina </td><td class=\"left\">5097.61 </td><td class=\"left\">13369.92 </td><td class=\"