2/aug/30/every-paralympic-athlete-and-their-sport-data","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/news/datablog/2012/aug/30/every-paralympic-athlete-and-their-sport-data","sectionName":"Sport"},{"webTitle":"London 2012 Paralympics: every team in numbers","webPublicationDate":"2012-08-30T07:00:00Z","sectionId":"news","id":"news/datablog/2012/aug/30/paralympic-teams-athlete-numbers-gender-data","fields":{"body":"<p>More than 4,000 athletes from 164 teams will compete over the next ten days at the 2012 Paralympic Games. Some countries are sending only a single athlete, while other teams are almost 300 strong.</p><p>Data from <a href=\"http://www.london2012.com/paralympics/athletes/\">the Games' official website</a> show that 4,286 competitors will take part, of which 2,776 - or roughly two thirds - are male.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.paralympics.org.uk/gb\">ParalympicsGB</a> has the largest team, with 294 competitors, followed by China, with 285, and the USA, with 223.</p><p>The teams from Brazil, Russia, Australia, France and Germany each consist of over 150 competitors, while Ukraine, Canada, Japan, Spain and Poland are the only other two countries bringing more than 100 to the Games.</p><p>Gender balance varies considerable between countries, with all-male and all-female teams taking part, though most of these are made up only a handful of athletes.</p><p>Rwanda and India are the largest male-only teams, with fourteen and ten members respectively. By contrast, Armenia, the largest female-only team, is made up of just two athletes.</p><p>Slovenia has the highest proportion of female competitors for any country with more than two team members. 15 of its 22 are female, largely a result of the women's sitting volleyball team, comprising eleven players, having qualified for the Games.</p><p>Of teams comprising 50 competitors or more, the five with the largest male proportion of athletes are Iran, Argentina, Thailand, Spain and South Africa.</p><p>Only 30 of Spain's 133 athletes are female, although this is due in part to the fact that the Spanish men's teams for wheelchair basketball and 5-a-side football both qualified for the Games, accounting for a total of 22 competitors, while Spain's female team members are competing predominantly in individual events.</p><p>The five teams with the highest female proportion of athletes (50 competitors or more) are Mexico, the Netherlands, China, Australia and Ukraine. Of these, only the top two are majority female.</p><p>45 countries are sending only one competitor, with a further 33 sending two each. Of the 164 teams taking part, 22 are sending more than 50 athletes.</p><h2>Data summary</h2><table>\n      <caption>\n            Numbers of male and female athletes for every team competing at the Paralympic Games\n          </caption>\n      <thead>\n        <tr><th class=\"bold left\">Country</th><th class=\"bold left\">Male</th><th class=\"bold left\">Female</th><th class=\"bold left\">Total</th><th class=\"bold left\">Percentage male</th></tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr><td class=\"left\">Great Britain </td><td class=\"left\">182 </td><td class=\"left\">112 </td><td class=\"left\">294 </td><td class=\"left\">61.9 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">China </td><td class=\"left\">159 </td><td class=\"left\">126 </td><td class=\"left\">285 </td><td class=\"left\">55.79 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">USA </td><td class=\"left\">130 </td><td class=\"left\">93 </td><td class=\"left\">223 </td><td class=\"left\">58.3 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Brazil </td><td class=\"left\">115 </td><td class=\"left\">68 </td><td class=\"left\">183 </td><td class=\"left\">62.84 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Russia </td><td class=\"left\">121 </td><td class=\"left\">62 </td><td class=\"left\">183 </td><td class=\"left\">66.12 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Australia </td><td class=\"left\">90 </td><td class=\"left\">71 </td><td class=\"left\">161 </td><td class=\"left\">55.9 </td></tr><t