ref=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2010/6/4/1275648032608/Guns-002.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2012/jul/22/gun-homicides-ownership-world-list","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/news/datablog/2012/jul/22/gun-homicides-ownership-world-list","sectionName":"News"},{"webTitle":"Ten golden moments to look out for at London 2012","webPublicationDate":"2012-07-20T22:03:17Z","sectionId":"sport","id":"sport/blog/2012/jul/20/10-olympic-moments-to-watch","fields":{"body":"<h2>1. Men's 100m final, <strong>Sunday 5 Aug 9.50pm</strong></h2><p>To understand just how special this 100m final is likely to be, you need to cast your mind back to the Beijing Olympic Games in 2008. It was there, in the Bird's Nest, that Usain Bolt reinvented the 100m, smashing his own world record – despite slowing down to celebrate 10m from the finish line – and obliterating the rest of the field. In his own words he \"blew the world's mind\". As he celebrated his extraordinary achievement, 9.69seconds on a go slow, the young Jamaican danced the \"Nuh Linga\" barefoot, his arms intertwined with the Jamaica flag, spikes in his huge hands. It is easy to forget that the International Olympic Committee president, Jacques Rogge, criticised him at the time for showboating. Since then Bolt's antics have become the sport's biggest selling point.</p><p>Over the following four years that magical moment in Beijing has become legendary. And since then Bolt has, for the most part, looked invincible. Three more world records followed at the world championships in 2009. In five years Bolt has been defeated only three times. That is quite a record.</p><p>For a long time it seemed that no one would ever beat him in a major championship final. This year, though, it may happen. Bolt's training partner, Yohan Blake, inherited the 100m world title after Bolt false-started in the final last year. Some dismissed that victory as a fluke but at the Jamaican Olympic trials this summer Blake confirmed his pedigree. Blowing away the rest of the field, including Bolt, the 22-year-old posted the fastest time of the year to set up a thrilling contest in London. With USA's Justin Gatlin and Tyson Gay also coming into form the men's 100m is no longer just a phenomenal one-man show.</p><p>In Stratford the most competitive final in years is likely to unfold. Even if you are not lucky enough to have a ticket, even if you hate sport, if you watch one Olympic event, make it this one. <strong>Anna Kessel</strong></p><h2><strong>2. </strong>Women's 400m freestyle, Sunday 29 July 8.15pm</h2><p>The British press and public get so excited about Rebecca Adlington, goodness knows what they will make of Federica Pellegrini. The Italian, only 23, is Adlington's main rival for the 400m freestyle. She has won four world titles since Beijing, beating Adlington over 400m in both 2009 and 2011. She is implausibly glamorous, improbably beautiful and a complete diva. In 2009 she posed naked for Vogue, her body spray-painted gold. And earlier this year she did another nude shoot for Vanity Fair, flaunting her tattooed body in a series of snaps that showed her sharing hugs and kisses with her boyfriend in bed. Before she settled down with her current partner, the former world 100m freestyle champion Filippo Magnini, Pellegrini was in a relationship with another Italian swimmer, Luca Marin. He had been engaged to her French freestyle rival Laure Manaudou but he left her for Pellegrini. Two year's later Pellegrini took Manaudou's world title, too.</p><p>None of this has any bearing on Adlington, or the showdown between the pair in the pool, but it does all help make Pellegrini one of the most compelling personalities in her sport. She has more sprinting speed than Adlington, doubling-up the 400m with the 200m freestyle, while the Briton goes the other way and also swims in the 800m.</p><p>So their 400m contest is a battle between speed and endurance. Since Adlington defeated her in Beijing, Pellegrini has tended to get the better of her British rival, beating her in two world championship finals. This year both are behind France's Camille Muffat in the world rankings, so the 400m is going to be a three-way tussle.</p><p>Adlington will start as the favourite for the 800m freestyle title but she faces fierce competition from Pellegrini and Muffat in the 400m. If she can beat them, she will go down as one of the greatest Olympians in British history. <strong>Andy Bull</strong></p><h2><strong>3. </strong>Women's heptathlon, <strong>Friday 3 Aug 10.05am</strong></h2><p>Four years ago Jessica Ennis sat at home, her right ankle in a plaster cast, watching the Olympic Games on the TV and crying into a pillow. The Sheffield heptathlete had been the up-and-coming star expected to make an impact in Beijing. Instead she was sidelined by a potentially career-ending injury. Ennis was not a household name back then but fast forward to 2012 and the 26-year-old is the face of the Games, the nation's favourite athlete, with a stack of medals to her name including world indoor (pentathlon) and outdoor as well as European golds.</p><p>Until last summer it had looked as if Ennis would cruise to the Olympic title this year, such was her dominance. But at the world championships in Daegu everything changed. A terrible throw in the javelin – she was 21st out of 26 in her weakest event – left Ennis in dire straits and Tatyana Chernova, a 23-year-old Russian who won Olympic bronze in 2008, took the world title. Worse was to come in March this year as Ennis was again unable to defend her world title – indoors this time – with the defending Olympic champion, Nataliya Dobrynska, winning gold.Just as sceptics began doubting her chances, Ennis hit back in May, beating the world's elite in Götzis with a personal best of 6,906 points, making her the eighth best heptathlete ever. And she reckons she has only just begun to show her potential.</p><p>With Ennis in the prime of her life, the battle between her and Chernova is bound to be fascinating. While the Briton's compact stature helps her to excel in the 100m hurdles, the first event, and 200m dash, as well as assisting her to victory in the high jump – all on the first day of the competition – the 6ft 2in Russian comes into her own on day two in the long jump, javelin and the strength-sapping 800m, the seventh and final event at 8.35pm on Saturday.</p><p>The defending champion, Dobrynska, cannot be written off either, nor can the USA's Beijing silver medallist, Hyleas Fountain.</p><p>Whether Ennis' newest domestic rival, the Liverpudlian world youth champion, Katarina Johnson-Thompson, who recently smashed Ennis's junior record, can make any impression on her Oympic debut will add further interest.<strong>Anna Kessel</strong></p><h2><strong>4. Men's individual platform diving, Saturday 11 Aug 8.30pm</strong></h2><p>Platform diving is one of the classic Olympic sports. For three years and 50 weeks of the cycle no one pays it much attention and most people could not be bothered to press the red button to watch it. But for the 14 days the competition lasts, everyone is a fan and a fair few start fancying themselves as experts too: \"Just look how little splash he made on that tucked four-and-a-half-somersault!\"</p><p>Even if Tom Daley were not competing, the diving would be worth tuning in for – it is breathtakingly beautiful, and mind-bogglingly athletic – but his participation means it is going to be one of the must-see events. It has been five years since Daley started making headlines as a 13-year-old. Since then he finished seventh at the Beijing Olympics, won the world championship, three BBC Young Sports Personality of the Year awards, two European titles and a Commonwealth gold. He has also had to do an awful lot of growing up in the public eye. He had a public falling out with his dive partner Blake Aldridge in Beijing, lost his father Rob to cancer in 2011 and had a spat with GB's performance director, Alexei Evangulov, who accused him of being too distracted by his commercial work. All the while his life seems to have been building towards the 2012 Olympics.</p><p>Daley is not favourite for the gold. That is Qiu Bo, the Chinese world No1 who is a level above and beyond everyone else. \"Nobody's going to beat him unless he drops a dive. If he doesn't drop, he won't be beaten,\" says Daley's coach, Andy Banks, of Bo.</p><p>But there is some cause for hope – in the past Bo has tended to crack under pressure. He did at Beijing in 2008 and again at the world championships in 2009. <strong>Andy Bull</strong></p><h2><strong>5. Women's match sprint, Tuesday 7 Aug 5.26pm</strong></h2><p>The two divas of sprint cycling, Anna Meares and Victoria Pendleton, between them have more history than Time Team but forget the wars of words, the difference in their approach and their temperaments. What makes their rivalry unique is how hard they can drive each other. If they meet in a semi-final the duel always leaves the winner emotionally and physically drained for the final.</p><p>Their contest for the world championship semi-final in Melbourne this year was the high point to date, including a crash for Pendleton and interventions by the judges as the pair pushed the rules of racing to the very limit. It swung first one way, then the other, with Pendleton coming out the unexpected winner for the sixth world title of her career.</p><p>Their rivalry goes back to 2006, when Meares cut her English rival up in a Derny-paced race. In 2008, in winning the Olympic final, Pendleton declared that she had wanted to humiliate the Australian rather than merely beat her. Since then there has been much debate over whether the pair actually detest each other or would really like to go out for a beer or three.</p><p>The far more muscular Meares uses her sheer strength and qualifying speed to establish an advantage from the start of a sprint tournament, whereas Pendleton, mentally more fragile as well as physically susceptible to injury, is a slower qualifier who relies on her superior pedalling speed. Recently Meares has looked to have the upper hand, winning last year's world title and two gold medals at the world's this year, but Pendleton now has momentum on her side and has gained in self-belief. The ultimate twist, however, is that Pendleton will quit after London. This time round it is not just personal; it is final. <strong>William Fotheringham</strong></p><h2><strong>6. Women's pole vault, Monday 6 Aug 7pm</strong></h2><p>A more contrasting pair could not be imagined: Yelena Isinbayeva, the pole vault world indoor and outdoor record holder and known for being one of the most glamorous female athletes on the circuit, versus Preston's Holly Bleasdale, a down-to- earth Lancashire lass, aged  20, who began pole vaulting only in late 2008.</p><p>In a remarkable rise Bleasdale has progressed from a bronze medal at the world junior championships in 2010, Britain's first global medal for a female pole vaulter, with a then career best that ranked her 62nd in the world to the second-highest indoor jump in history after clearing 4.87m in January this year.</p><p>Meanwhile Isinbayeva, a regular magazine cover star, has struggled for form in recent years. The Russian, who has set 28 records in the event, even prompted speculation that she might retire after a series of difficult years – posting three no-jumps at the 2009 world championships and failing to gain any sort of medal at the world indoor championships in 2010 and again at the worlds in 2011. It was there, in Daegu, that Bleasdale rued missing her chance to capitalise on the most recent failure and burst into tears after she failed to register a height in the final.</p><p>This season, however, both women are on form to make this an intriguing and compelling contest. Isinbayeva won the world indoor title in March, where Bleasdale finished third. Then the Briton broke her own national record in poor weather at the Olympic trials in June, propelling her to fifth in the world rankings for this, her breakthrough, season. <strong>Anna Kessel</strong></p><h2><strong>7. Men's 10,000m, Saturday 4 Aug 9.15pm</strong></h2><p>Less than two years ago the notion that Mo Farah would challenge for Kenenisa Bekele's Olympic titles at 5,000m and 10,000m would have seemed bonkers. Back in 2010 Farah's double victory at the European Championships had been impressive but it certainly did not position him as a serious contender on the global stage . He was not even in the world top 10.</p><p>Bekele, by contrast, was – and still is – one of the most astonishing distance runners that ever lived. Unbeaten in the 10,000m between 2003 and 2011, the Ethiopian has three Olympic, five world track and 11 world cross-country titles. He is also the world and Olympic record holder for both events.</p><p>But a major change for Farah – moving to Portland, Oregon, to work under the idiosyncratic coach Alberto Salazar – has seen the Somalia-born Briton pick up a world title over 5,000m, a world silver medal over 10,000m and top the current world rankings. Suddenly the 29-year-old Londoner is looking more and more like the man to beat.</p><p>Key to Farah's success seems to be his ability to embrace knowledge and expertise from two sides of the globe – east and west – in his quest to become the Olympic champion. After living with a group of Kenyan runners during his student days – and observing their near monastic lifestyle of ugali (maize porridge), running and religious TV – Farah has adopted these austere principles. While the rest of the west moaned about East Africans dominating distance running Farah simply beat the opposition at their own game, spending months at a time training at altitude in Kenya, living in basic conditions. At the same time, under Salazar, Farah embraced western technology to improve his training – including an underwater treadmill to prevent injury and a cooling chamber that blasts liquid nitrogen at –300C at his body.</p><p>Who wins may depend on which Bekele starts the race: the one who has struggled with injury of late – dropping out of the 10,000m world championships final last year – or the sensational runner who still set the world's fastest time last year over the distance. <strong>Anna Kessel</strong></p><h2><strong>8. Men's 400m individual medley and 200m individual medley, Saturday 28 Jul 7.30pm &amp; Thursday 2 Aug 8.16pm</strong></h2><p>For Michael Phelps the Beijing Olympics were a procession but London 2012 will be a battle. For the first time Phelps faces a genuine rival to the title of the greatest swimmer in the world – his team-mate Ryan Lochte. The fight between the two of them is going to be one of the defining contests of the Games. Phelps is certain to swim in seven events, Lochte is likely to do six and each expects to win gold in every one. At least one of them is going to be disappointed. Lochte and Phelps, both 27, will go head-to-head in the 200m and 400m medleys, an all-round test of stamina, technique and speed in which the swimmers have to perform all four strokes.</p><p>At the US trials in Omaha, Nebraska, Phelps and Lochte went head-to-head in four events. Phelps won three – the 200m IM, the 200m freestyle and 100m butterfly – while Lochte took the 400m medley. But Phelps's combined margin of victory was a mere three-tenths of a second. Lochte's winning margin was 0.83sec. Of the 16 50m splits the two rivals swam in finals, Phelps was faster in eight, Lochte in seven and there was one tie. Lochte is the world record holder for the 200m medley, Phelps in the 400m. All of which is another way of saying that there is almost nothing between them.</p><p>Phelps has already won more gold medals than any Olympian in history – eight in Beijing, six in Athens. He needs three more medals, of any colour, to overtake the Russian gymnast Larisa Latynina as the most decorated Olympian ever. The Aquatics Centre should see his coronation as the greatest competitor in Olympic history but it could also see him lose his crown as the best swimmer in the world. <strong>Andy Bull</strong></p><h2><strong>9. Men's four final, Saturday 4 Aug 10.30am</strong></h2><p>There is only one Olympic sport, away from the swimming pool, in which the winners cross the line backwards. It means the leaders can see their pursuers gaining on them, one of the reasons why top-class rowing can be such a compelling spectacle. Think of Steve Redgrave, Matthew Pinsent, James Cracknell and Tim Foster chasing down the Italians in Sydney in 2000, judging their surge to perfection. A similarly epic contest beckons in perhaps the flagship race of the 2012 Games, the men's four.</p><p>In the red, white and blue will be the quartet of Alex Gregory, Andrew Triggs-Hodge, Pete Reed and Tom James. Determined to ruin everything is the Australian crew of William Lockwood, James Chapman, Drew Ginn and Joshua Dunkley-Smith. It will have the crackle of Lord's on the first morning of an Ashes Test, albeit on a slightly damper pitch.</p><p>The rivalry between the two crews is already intense. Great Britain won the first two World Cup events in Belgrade and Lucerne this year, establishing a new world-best time in the latter race. Subsequently, though, the British quartet suffered two defeats in Munich last month. The Poms started poorly in the final and duly finished second. The spur of competing on home water should make a difference and the British four are also the reigning Olympic champions. Last time in Beijing – with Steve Williams in the boat rather than Gregory – they saw off Australia and France in a thrilling finish, coming from behind over the final 220 metres to pip the Aussies.</p><p>Triggs-Hodge and Reed, a naval officer, subsequently opted to row as a pair before reverting to their original boat. Gregory, from Worcestershire, and James, a proud Welshman, were born on the same day in March 1984. If the quartet can win again, it will be a triumph of competitive will as much as anything else. British rowing is hoping for a memorable Games and this race could be the thrilling pinnacle. <strong>Robert Kitson</strong></p><h2><strong>10. Men's road race, Saturday 28 July 10am</strong></h2><p>A potential thriller on day one of the Games with a true British sporting great in centre stage, the twist being that crossing the line first will be the biggest ask of Mark Cavendish's career. Taking the gold medal is by no means a given and may prove beyond him but he has embraced the challenge wholeheartedly.</p><p>The Manxman is legendary as the fastest sprinter in the world on a flat course, with a massive tally of stage wins in the Tour de France and a world road race title to his name. But the circuit over Box Hill is a different proposition – to have a chance of getting over the long, steep climb nine times at race speed he has had to lose half a stone in weight, sacrificing a little of his famous sprint velocity, and he has trained specially over the climb behind a motorbike to simulate race conditions. A one-day race over this kind of circuit is impossible to predict, will be hard to read on the day and, with only five riders per team, will be the devil itself to control. It is a lottery but the dream scenario for Cavendish is that the field is in one big group when the race arrives for the finish on The Mall.</p><p>All the other nations in the race will know that, if that is the scenario, he is likely to win, so they will spend most of the 250km trying to burn him off and his four team-mates will try to prevent them. It should be a full-blooded spectacle. What is at stake for Cavendish – a gold medal at home, on top of the world road race title he won last year – is what makes this one enthralling but the uncertainty makes it unique. <strong>William Fotheringham</strong></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2012/7/10/1341915037562/Olympics---Jessica-Ennis-003.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2012/jul/20/10-olympic-moments-to-watch","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog/2012/jul/20/10-olympic-moments-to-watch","sectionName":"Sport"},{"webTitle":"Britons in trouble abroad: where are you most likely to be arrested? Get the data","webPublicationDate":"2012-07-19T08:00:00Z","sectionId":"news","id":"news/datablog/2012/jul/19/britons-in-trouble-abroad-data-fco-advice","fields":{"body":"<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) handled 19,874 assistance cases for overseas Britons between April 2011 and March 2012, including reports of sexual assault and requests for help following drug arrests.</p><p>The figures, published in the 2012 British Behaviour Abroad report, show a 3% year-on-year rise in total cases, and a 10% increase in reports of rape.</p><p>In 2011 an average of more than ten British people were hospitalised every day while abroad. Spain saw an 8% jump in the number of hospitalisations reported to consular staff compared to 2010.</p><p>The upward trend in hospitalisation cases, of which 30% of all instances concerned Britons in Spain, is covered <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2012/jul/19/young-uk-holidaymakers-spanish-hospitals\">here in greater detail</a> by Lisa Bachelor and Jill Insley, who write:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The renowned party island of Mallorca has seen a 132% increase in hospitalisations over the two years to the end of March 2012, while Ibiza has seen a 40% increase.</p></blockquote><p>Other assistance cases concerned deaths, reports of sexual assault and requests for emergency travel documentation. The latter accounted for 28,659 separate cases in 2011/12.</p><p>The interactive map below, produced by the FCO, shows numbers of cases reported by Britons in each country. Use the drop-down menu to view statistics for different categories (the default view is total cases).</p><p>For a better illustration of how countries compare, the rate of cases per Briton in a given country is a more useful statistic. The chart below lists the 20 destinations with the highest number of cases reported per 10,000 British residents or visitors.</p><p>The Philippines ranks as the most trouble-fraught destination, with the FCO handling more than 20 assistance cases for every 10,000 Britons living or visiting the islands in 2011/12.</p><p>Thailand and Jamaica sit second and third, and are the only two other countries with rates of more than ten cases per 10,000 Britons.</p><p>Despite accounting nominally for more cases than any other country worldwide, Spain fares better with this measure, given the enormous volume of Britons who either reside or holiday there.</p><p>The FCO received more than 5,000 requests for assistance in 2011/12 from people in Spain, but spread across the 13 million Britons spending time in the country this is a less disturbing sum than it initially appears.</p><p>If you are an expat or are planning to holiday abroad this summer, and are worried about contributing to the statistics for 2012/13, <a href=\"http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/travel-and-living-abroad/\">click here for the FCO's advice on travel and living abroad.</a></p><h2>Data summary</h2><table>\n      <caption>\n            Brits in trouble abroad: all cases by type and country\n          </caption>\n      <thead>\n        <tr><th class=\"bold left\">Country</th><th class=\"bold left\">Drug \nArrests</th><th class=\"bold left\">Total Arrests</th><th class=\"bold left\">Deaths</th><th class=\"bold left\">Hosp- italis- ation</th><th class=\"bold left\">Rape</th><th class=\"bold left\">Sexual \nAssault</th><th class=\"bold left\">Other Assis- tance</th><th class=\"bold left\">Total \nAssis- tance</th><th class=\"bold left\">Emergency travel documents</th></tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr><td class=\"left\">Afghanistan </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">5 </td><td class=\"right\">5 </td><td class=\"right\">2 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">7 </td><td class=\"right\">19 </td><td class=\"right\">3 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Albania </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">4 </td><td class=\"right\">12 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Algeria </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">6 </td><td class=\"right\">8 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Angola </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">1 </td><td class=\"right\">3 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Anguilla </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td class=\"right\">0 </td><td cla