 to hit targets of treating 15 million people who are living with HIV. Progress has been especially impressive in sub-Saharan Africa, the report said, where nearly 6.2 million people were receiving antiretroviral treatment in 2011 – up from only 100,000 in 2003.</p><p>The improved treatment level has saved lives – with the estimated life-years saved in the region increasing more than fourfold between 2008 and 2011. The number of deaths from Aids-related causes in the region has declined from a peak of 1.8 million a year in 2005 – to 1.2 million in 2011.</p><p>The 21 priority countries in sub-Saharan Africa account for 90% of pregnant women living with HIV worldwide – making their progress crucial in hitting the target of halving the number of pregnant women dying from Aids-related causes.</p><p>Among those countries and India, the number of pregnancy-related deaths among mothers with HIV fell from 41,500 in 2005 to 33,000 in 2010.</p><p>Michel Sidibé, executive director of UNAids, said: \"With the momentum being generated by the global plan towards the elimination of new HIV infections among children by 2015 and keeping their mothers alive, the international community has set a strong course to achieve an Aids-free generation.\"</p><p>Source: <a href=\"http://www.unaids.org/en/\">UNAIDS</a></p><p>Source: <a href=\"http://www.unaids.org/en/\">UNAIDS</a></p><h2>Data summary</h2><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a name=\"data\"></p><h2>Download the data</h2><p></a></p><p>• <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AhORuxOwZhGydFNELXRxVm5ISVF3X1dCOXF0NUxZSWc\">DATA: download the first spreadsheet</a><br />• <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AhORuxOwZhGydDRjVG1GZng5cDNBQTVILVQ4WGlsWnc\">DATA: download the second spreadsheet</a></p><h2>More data</h2><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data\">More data journalism and data visualisations from the Guardian</a></p><h2>World government data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world-government-data\">Search the world's government data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Development and aid data</h2><p>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store/global-development-data/search?q=\">Search the world's global development data with our gateway</a></p><h2>Can you do something with this data?</h2><p>• <strong>Flickr</strong> Please post your visualisations and mash-ups on our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/guardiandata\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2010/9/18/1284823402979/The-mother-of-a-young-chi-002.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/datablog/2012/jul/18/sub-saharan-africa-child-hiv-infection-unaids","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/global-development/datablog/2012/jul/18/sub-saharan-africa-child-hiv-infection-unaids","sectionName":"Global development"},{"webTitle":"Which are the laziest countries on earth?","webPublicationDate":"2012-07-18T11:24:00Z","sectionId":"news","id":"news/datablog/2012/jul/18/physical-inactivity-country-laziest","fields":{"body":"<p>This may be an <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/series/london-2012-olympics-data\">Olympic summer</a>, but the majority of Britons are more likely to watch the athletes rather than try and emulate them. </p><p>Research <a href=\"http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(12)60816-2/abstract\">published in the Lancet today</a> shows that the UK, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2012/jul/18/uk-inactive-population-europe\">Sarah Boseley writes</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>has the third most slothful population in Europe, with two-thirds of adults failing to take enough physical exercise to keep themselves healthy, according to research. Only in Malta and Serbia do the over-15s exert themselves less than in the UK</p></blockquote><p>The report shows that:</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>• In the UK, 63.3% of adults (with higher rates in women than in men) do not meet recommended amounts of activity, such as walking briskly for 30 minutes or more five times a week or taking more vigorous exercise for 20 minutes three times a week<br />• The US scores 41% and Canada 34%<br />• In Malta, 71.9% of adults are inactive and in Serbia the proportion is 68.3%<br />• The most active countries are Greece, where 16% are inactive, Estonia (17%) and the Netherlands (18%)</p><p>Inactivity causes between 6% and 10% of four major diseases – coronary heart disease, type 2 diabetes and breast and colon cancer, reported the Lancet. In 2008, it was responsible for about 5.3 million out of the 57 million deaths worldwide.</p><p>The full data is <a href=\"#data\">below</a>. What can you do with it?</p><h2>Data summary</h2><table>\n      <caption>\n            Inactive adults rate by country\n          </caption>\n      <thead>\n        <tr><th class=\"left\">Country</th><th class=\"left\">Region</th><th class=\"left\">Both sexes, %</th><th class=\"left\">Men, %</th><th class=\"left\">Women, %</th></tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr><td class=\"left\">Algeria </td><td class=\"left\">African Region  </td><td class=\"left\">40.5 </td><td class=\"left\">31.9 </td><td class=\"left\">49.2 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Benin </td><td class=\"left\">African Region  </td><td class=\"left\">9.1 </td><td class=\"left\">7.1 </td><td class=\"left\">11.2 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Botswana </td><td class=\"left\">African Region  </td><td class=\"