our <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/groups/1115946@N24/\">Flickr group</a><br />• Contact us at <a href=\"mailto:data@guardian.co.uk\">data@guardian.co.uk</a></p><p><strong>• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/page/2009/jun/17/1\">Get the A-Z of data</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/data-store\">More at the Datastore directory</a></strong><br /><strong>• <a href=\"http://twitter.com/datastore\">Follow us on Twitter</a><br />• <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/Guardian-data/155291341187950\">Like us on Facebook</a></strong></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/11/25/1322239371716/A-woman-smokes-a-cigarett-004.jpg"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2012/mar/23/tobacco-industry-atlas-smoking","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/news/datablog/2012/mar/23/tobacco-industry-atlas-smoking","sectionName":"News"},{"webTitle":"World water day: which countries have improved access to safe drinking water?","webPublicationDate":"2012-03-22T17:51:00Z","sectionId":"news","id":"news/datablog/2012/mar/22/who-water-sanitation-goals","fields":{"body":"<p>Today is <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/gallery/2012/mar/22/world-water-day-2012-gallery?newsfeed=true\">world water day</a>. It comes in a week when UNICEF and World Health Organisation (WHO) <a href=\"http://www.wssinfo.org/fileadmin/user_upload/resources/JMP-report-2012-en.pdf\">announced</a> that the millenium development goal on drinking water access has been met ahead of time.</p><p>The goal for clean is described <a href=\"http://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/pdf/MDG%20Report%202010%20En%20r15%20-low%20res%2020100615%20-.pdf#page=60\">in detail on the United Nations website</a> but in simple terms the target is to: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Halve, by 2015, the proportion of people without sustainable access to safe drinking-water and basic sanitation</p></blockquote><p>The WHO and Unicef <a href=\"http://www.wssinfo.org/about-the-jmp/introduction/\">joint monitoring programme</a> (JMP) for water supply and sanitation, has been gathering data to measure the goal. They found that between 1990 and 2010 more than 2 billion people gained access to improved drinking water.</p><p>As you can see from the JMP chart above - that 2 billon people has halved the number of people without access to safe drinking water.  </p><p>That means that 89% of the world population, or 6.1 billion people, had access to an improved source of drinking water in 2010.</p><p>But is the JMP measure of the drinking water situation fair? </p><p>There is some suggestion that the  measure doens't take into account the large amount of variation between countries. </p><p>As the Guardian's <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/lizford\">Liz Ford</a> has <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/global-development/2012/mar/06/water-millennium-development-goals\">noted</a>:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The report said huge regional disparities existed. Almost half of the 2 billion people who have gained access to drinking water since 1990 live in China or India. Meanwhile, many countries in Africa are not on track to meet the target by 2015, with some countries actually falling back to pre-1990 rates of coverage. More than 40% of all people globally who lack access to drinking water live in sub-Saharan Africa.</p></blockquote><p>This variation is clear from the JMP map:</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-387982383'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/3/22/1332419792410/World-map-MDG-water-001.jpg' alt='World map MDG water' width='460' height='306' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>World map. The blue areas are countries on track to meet the MDG target. The orange areas are not on track to meet the safe drinking water goals by 2015. </figcaption></figure><p>The JMP data is here for you to <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0AonYZs4MzlZbdHhIVE5NSTVfMkxKR1hrbFMyRW5WTkE\">download</a> and showing the variation between urban and rural regions for every country being monitored.   </p><p>What can you do to show the disparity between the countries and their drinking water quality? Do you think the safe drinking water goal is fair?</p><h2>Data summary</h2><table>\n      <caption>\n            The WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) water supply improvements\n          </caption>\n      <thead>\n        <tr><th class=\"bold left\">Country</th><th class=\"bold left\">2010 National Water Total Improved (x1000)</th><th class=\"bold left\">2010 National Water  Total Improved (%)</th><th class=\"bold left\">1990 National Water Total Improved (x1000)</th><th class=\"bold left\">1990 National Water  Total Improved (%)</th></tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr><td class=\"left\">Afghanistan </td><td class=\"left\">15749 </td><td class=\"left\">50 </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Albania </td><td class=\"left\">3045 </td><td class=\"left\">95 </td><td class=\"left\">3206 </td><td class=\"left\">97 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Algeria </td><td class=\"left\">29435 </td><td class=\"left\">83 </td><td class=\"left\">23845 </td><td class=\"left\">94 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Andorra </td><td class=\"left\">85 </td><td class=\"left\">100 </td><td class=\"left\">53 </td><td class=\"left\">100 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Angola </td><td class=\"left\">9707 </td><td class=\"left\">51 </td><td class=\"left\">4364 </td><td class=\"left\">42 </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Anguilla </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Antigua and Barbuda </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td></tr><tr><td class=\"left\">Argentina </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"\"> </td><td class=\"left\">30601 </td><td class=\"left\">94 </td></tr><tr><td cl